{
  "text": "Furthermore, given the common representation of genes as deterministic, conferring immutable effects, it is important to document the impact of DNA testing for nicotine responsiveness in the longer term upon attributions for failure to quit smoking among those smokers who do not quit. Informing patients that their prescription is tailored to their genotype may have negative effects through engendering a sense of fatalism, which is associated with perceiving a genetic cause to a health problem [CITATION_1] . Such fatalistic responses are predicted to result in reduced motivation in this group to make a future quit attempt (amongst those who fail to quit by six months).",
  "citation_candidates": [
